I thought I'd have a go at making my own!
Designed roughly from the attached schematic, this takes two 625 2RS bearings, one either side, either an eccentric spacer or standard 6mm spacer and a 5mm bolt and nylock nut to complete.  You will also need an OpenBuilds gantry plate to bolt the wheels to and, of course, a corresponding OpenBuilds rail!
Unfortunately, my printer is busted at the moment, but I'd love to hear if someone prints and uses this!  I would advise using ABS (print slightly oversize to compensate for shrinkage as these sizes are exact!)  I think PLA would be too brittle under the stresses.

description.text: This kit is a remix of a handful of assorted sets of cable chains for the Printrbot Simple Metal.  I found that none of them were a full solution or that they had some minor fit problems on my machine, so I modified the attachment points and some links, and have repackaged for your benefit.

Parts Links:
1x 45-out
12x 90-in
13x 90-out
2x offset-in
1x offset-out
1x extruder Attachment points:
1x E Motor Mount
1x Front Attachment Point
1x Rear Attachment Point
1x Y Motor Mount Installation Instructions Once the pieces are printed, you will be able to install the chain without disassembling your Printrbot. The pieces are designed to snap around the cable. Make sure you have removed the original cable wrapping, and loosened the cables from underneath to ensure you have enough slack during installation. Links will be installed in an alternating in-out order. Note that when I say "in", these are the links that have their U-shape pointing inwards. "Out" pieces have their opening pointing outwards and have a small channel accross the long side. Rear Chain 1) Install the Rear Attachment Point at the back of the Printrbot. Use a short M3 screw to attack to the hole in the back of the printer. You may need to trim your grommet slightly to ensure a snug fit.
2) The order of links is as follows: 45-out, 6x(90-in, 90-out)
3) Slide the Y Motor Mount around the Y motor, with the cable attach point facing the rear. There are small tabs you can use to secure it with a zip tie.
4) Connect the chain to the motor mount. Front Chain 1) Install the Front Attachment Point on the base of the printer. It will install under two of the screws used to hold the Z-axis rods. You may need to trim your grommet for a secure fit.
2) The order of links is as follows: 5x(90-out, 90-in), 90-out, offset-in, offset-out, offset-in, 90-out, 90-in, extruder.
3) Install the E Motor Mount around the extruder motor. There are slots to allow you to put a zip tie fully around the assembly to secure it.
4) Connect the chain to the motor mount. Notes You can safely install the front chain around the hotend/thermistor couplings that are on the cable. I have encountered no issues with this. You may need M3 screws that are 1-2mm longer than you currently have holding your z-axis rods. If you did a kit, you will probably have spares already. Otherwise, pop over to your local Home Depot and take care of that. You will also need a short (~8mm) M3 screw for the back side. Depending on the size of your cable grommets, you may need to trim the edges slightly to allow the attachment points to sit flush with the body. After everything is installed, use Cura to move the Z and Y axes to their full extensoin and ensure the cable chains are not being stretched. Once you are satisfied with the range of motion, use zip ties to secure and tidy up the excess cabling in the bottom of the printer.

• Remove the top 2 screws for the right-hand Y-axle cover plate (the one closest to the Y- belt idler).
  • Place the bracket over the head of the idler bolt and position it in place resting on top of the axle. (some trimming of holes to make it fit might be required)
  • Replace screws in the axle cover plate with the nuts fitting in the nut wells of the new bracket. (I was able to get the nuts to suck into the part by fitting them with the screws before installing)
  • Adjust belt tension, if necessary.

I have been experimenting with enclosing liquids in sealed printed volumes. You fill this one up with some food-coloring-dyed water and then flip it around and such. Video: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NhiofHqA2hY

DISCLAIMER: By attempting to build this you agree to not hold Trevor Law liable for anything bad that happens to you.
(1) Printing: Depending on your printer's performance and settings, you may need to change how many layers you do for the base and top.  Most important things are bridge performance and layer height.  Of course, you must use a translucent/transparent plastic.
(2) Sealing: I have tried several methods.  For all of these ENSURE ADEQUATE VENTILATION because fumes may be harmful.  Also do not burn yourself with hot plastic or metal or anything.  I am not a safety expert and don't know if any of these methods are safe.
(2a) The pictured piece was remelted as gently as possible in the oven to make the strands go together, which greatly improves visibility.  If you do it too long, the void will almost certainly collapse.  On my kitchen oven somewhere between 290-310 F seems to melt it enough.  This should ensure water-tightness as long as there were not substantial holes before melting.
(2b) I have also tried polyurethane varnish.  In my experience, you cannot use this to close up visible holes because its viscosity is too low, but it can seal up a good print without major defects.  It may also slightly improve visibility.
(2c) Instead of the oven, heat up one or both of the bases on a stove, melting the strands together.  This is currently my preferred method, since it supports the wall you are melting, reducing the likelihood of collapse.  Unfortunately it only works on flat surfaces around the exterior of a part.
(3)Filling: Drill holes, inject water, and seal up with a sealant.  You need 2 holes, preferably on opposite sides of the part, or else pressure will build up and prevent you from injecting liquid.  In my opinion, the smaller the hole, the better, since it will be easier to seal.  However, keep in mind that surface tension can make it very difficult to get liquid in, you will want a tool that can fit through the hole.  I do not have any syringes handy, so I have been using a pipette tip with an eye dropper stuck into the wider end.
(4) Flip it around and watch the water.  The water moves much easier if you only have one bubble, which you can achieve by flicking the part with your finger to make the fluid flow to the bottom (the shock breaks the surface tension so that bubble and fluid can change places).  One interesting thing you can do is get a single bubble at the top, and then flip it while keeping it as straight as possible.  It will act like an inverted pendulum, and a slight imbalance will send the bubble up one way or the other.

comments.text: Only if you are not going to do any remelting afterwards, boiling point of water is 212 F.  That means you can only get up to 212 F until all the water evaporates.  I don't have a lot of hands-on experience here, but I think that would be dangerous to try.  If you got a gas-tight or near gas-tight print you can in theory get over 212 F but the vapor pressure of the water inside will be greater than atmospheric pressure.  That means a steam explosion of some magnitude is possible when the pla adequately weakens (My guess is not so big, but big enough to burn you, and in any case, no more part).

description.text: This project turns an ordinary set of headphones into a full communications headset by adding a microphone mounted on a boom. The mic boom is held in place with a magnet and can be flipped up or removed. A base or mount is attached to the headphones with double-sided tape.

Notes:

  • If your customized design ends up with a bump on the back of the mic holder, you may want to use your slicer's feature to sink the model below the surface of the bed slightly so it sits flat.

  • You may need to use a brim for adhesion.

Assembly

  • Put the microphone into the holder and gently work the cord into the gap. Don't use any sharp objects but a fingernail or popsicle stick could help.

  • Depending on how tight the magnets are, you might need to use pliers to press the magnets into the recesses. Take care not to smash the bumps on the boom! Use spare magnets to give you a spacer to keep the pliers off the bumps.

  • Make sure the magnets are facing the right way! I put a dot on the side that's not visible with a sharpie marker so I wouldn't get confused. You may need a dab of superglue or epoxy to keep the magnets in.

  • Use double-sided tape to attach the mount to your headphones. I recommend putting the assembly on the same side as the headphones existing cord.

  • If the microphone is too far away after attaching to your headphones, you can gently heat the boom shaft with hot water, a hair dryer or heatgun and gently bend it. This needs to be done after inserting the cable, but be very careful not to melt the insulation on the wires.

  • Finally, for issues on using the microphone, see my earlier version on instructables.com for info on adjusting mic levels, etc. http://www.instructables.com/id/Universal-Headset-Microphone-Boom/

You need the following:
  • 3D Print of the Boom part
  • 3D Print of the Mount part
  • One small Electret Condenser Microphone
  • Two small cylindrical rare earth magnets
  • Superglue or Epoxy
  • Good quality double sided tape
    • Notes:

For the magnets, I used small rare-earth magnets from Harbor Freight (http://www.harborfreight.com/10-piece-rare-earth-magnets-67488.html). For the double-sided tape, I used 3M brand '4011' outdoor mounting tape. The Superglue or epoxy is in case you need to glue in the magnets.

This is a car mount designed specifically for an iPhone 6S in the Apple Leather case. I realize that's pretty specific but I built it for myself and figured others might have a use for it as well. 
The design features a channel for an Apple lightning cable. The channel securely captures the lightning connector by feeding the cable in perpendicular to the mount then, once the connector is through, rotate the connector to be parallel to the mount and push back into the channel. title: i3 X-Ends for LM8LUU and 8mm Anti-Backlash Nut

description.text:
I got a pair of TR8*4 leadscrews from RobotDigg, as well as the anti-backlash nut that require substantial changes to the X-ends on my Prusa i3.. so I'm designing my own. Linear Stepper Nema17 w/ 300mm Tr8*4 Leadscrew
http://www.robotdigg.com/product/557 Anti-backlash Nut for Tr8*4 Lead Screw
http://www.robotdigg.com/product/344 I designed the X-ends to hold a captive LM8LUU bearing (8x15x45mm), retained by M3 screws at the top and bottom. Since the diameter of the anti-backlash nut is rather large, this required that I space out the distance between the smooth rod and the threaded rod to 26 mm (vs 20). I will also be designing altered motor mounts for the Z axis to take this into consideration. work in progress Update 1: Printed out X motor end, it fits the bearing and 8mm nut well - but I had to revise the motor part to be a bit thicker. Also made the belt pathway wider, to 10mm, so it can handle a 9mm-wide belt.

title: CupCake Extruder type R with opposing motors

description.text:
Still in the draft stage but the best extruder I have used yet.  Two opposing motors.  this give a rock solid grip on the filament.  
Next revision will be making a tighter fit on the empty space around the pulley on each side.  
You may need to addjust the screw holes for the motor, if they get too tight the filament wraps like crazy (don't ask how I know)
Future will see this design refined and printed on the CupCake, two pieces, the one side will hold a motor including entry /exit for filament and hold the nozzle. The other side will dovetail and slide so the motor pulley can be adjusted for tightness to the other pulley, Im thinking it should have a bolt in the direction of the motion with a wingnut for adjustments. See sketch.  
ANYONE please feel free to design that mount, I am not terrible good at setting up parts with accurate screw holes etc. :-)
"Type R" as in BMW motorbikes, two opposed cylinders slightly offset.

This is a DRAFT design, but it works VERY well so far.  (at least for me)
I used 3mm acrylic material, it is actually a little too thin, so I mounted the two motors with a set of washers to pull them out a little and also wrapped a piece of tape around the center piece to make sure the filament would move smoothly.
To prevent the motors from pushing apart I glued the 4 layers on each side to a firm brick, this helped create a very firm mount.
The Dino is very rudimentary, only one piece of 3mm on each arm, I thought it would wobble, but it seems plenty firm.

title: Square Chamber Oil and Water Toy

description.text: Oil and colored water in an enclosed volume. The system has some interesting dynamics: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qKU1z01YzcA The OpenSCAD file is parametric, so you can experiment to change the flow parameters. The default parameters make the flow somewhat slow, so you could try to make bigger chambers/channels if your printer bridging performance is good enough. If someone knows of another safe immiscible fluid combination that is less viscous, I would be enjoy being told about it.

DISCLAIMER: By attempting to build this you agree to not hold Trevor Law liable for anything bad that happens to you.  ENSURE ADEQUATE VENTILATION because fumes may be harmful. Also do not burn yourself with hot plastic or metal or anything. I am not a safety expert and don't know if this method is safe.
(1) Printing: Make sure you can do bridges.  I advise you customize the base and top thickness to your liking.  Thinner can make visibility higher but make sealing for difficult.
(2) Sealing: I used a stove top with a cake pan from the 99 cent store.  I wouldn't use whatever you use here to prepare food in the future.  Heat until you can just see the bottom surface becoming clear.  Let cool before attempting removal.  You can do this to both large faces, or just make one thick enough to be water-tight without remelting.  The default 3mm side wall thickness made those walls water-tight in my experience.
(3) Filling: Drill two holes and opposite sides of an edge.  Fill.  I used pale blue food-coloring-colored water and vegetable oil.  Seal with safe and appropriate sealant.  If you have some bubbles it is not the end of the world, since they will provide some faster dynamics for the less patient.
